# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lean-prover
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] In the context of hardware and software systems, **formal verification** is the act of proving or disproving the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Formal verification is a key incentive for formal specification of systems, and is at the core of formal methods.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] It represents an important dimension of analysis and verification in electronic design automation and is one approach to software verification.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The use of formal verification enables the highest Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL7) in the framework of common criteria for computer security certification.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Formal verification can be helpful in proving the correctness of systems such as: cryptographic protocols, combinational circuits, digital circuits with internal memory, and software expressed as source code in a programming language.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Prominent examples of verified software systems include the CompCert verified C compiler and the seL4 high-assurance operating system kernel.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The verification of these systems is done by ensuring the existence of a formal proof of a mathematical model of the system.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Model checking involves a systematic and exhaustive exploration of the mathematical model.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Such exploration is possible for finite models, but also for some infinite models, where infinite sets of states can be effectively represented finitely by using abstraction or taking advantage of symmetry.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Usually, this consists of exploring all states and transitions in the model, by using smart and domain-specific abstraction techniques to consider whole groups of states in a single operation and reduce computing time.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Implementation techniques include state space enumeration, symbolic state space enumeration, abstract interpretation, symbolic simulation, abstraction refinement.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The properties to be verified are often described in temporal logics, such as linear temporal logic (LTL), Property Specification Language (PSL), SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA), or computational tree logic (CTL).
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Another approach is deductive verification.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Formal verification of software programs involves proving that a program satisfies a formal specification of its behavior.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Subareas of formal verification include deductive verification (see above), abstract interpretation, automated theorem proving, type systems, and lightweight formal methods.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] A promising type-based verification approach is dependently typed programming, in which the types of functions include (at least part of) those functions' specifications, and type-checking the code establishes its correctness against those specifications.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Fully featured dependently typed languages support deductive verification as a special case.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Another complementary approach is program derivation, in which efficient code is produced from functional specifications by a series of correctness-preserving steps.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] An example of this approach is the Bird–Meertens formalism, and this approach can be seen as another form of program synthesis.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] These techniques can be *sound*, meaning that the verified properties can be logically deduced from the semantics, or *unsound*, meaning that there is no such guarantee.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] A sound technique yields a result only once it has covered the entire space of possibilities.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] An example of an unsound technique is one that covers only a subset of the possibilities, for instance only integers up to a certain number, and give a "good-enough" result.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Techniques can also be *decidable*, meaning that their algorithmic implementations are guaranteed to terminate with an answer, or undecidable, meaning that they may never terminate.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] By bounding the scope of possibilities, unsound techniques that are decidable might be able to be constructed when no decidable sound techniques are available.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Verification is one aspect of testing a product's fitness for purpose.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Often one refers to the overall checking process as V & V.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The verification process consists of static/structural and dynamic/behavioral aspects.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] E.g., for a software product one can inspect the source code (static) and run against specific test cases (dynamic).
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Validation usually can be done only dynamically, i.e., the product is tested by putting it through typical and atypical usages ("Does it satisfactorily meet all use cases?").
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Program repair is performed with respect to an oracle, encompassing the desired functionality of the program which is used for validation of the generated fix.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] A simple example is a test-suite—the input/output pairs specify the functionality of the program.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] A variety of techniques are employed, most notably using satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solvers, and genetic programming, using evolutionary computing to generate and evaluate possible candidates for fixes.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The former method is deterministic, while the latter is randomized.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] For example, the Nopol tool encodes the repair of buggy conditional statements as an SMT instance to determinstically generate patches for if conditions and missing preconditions.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Program repair combines techniques from formal verification and program synthesis.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Fault-localization techniques in formal verification are used to compute program points which might be possible bug-locations, which can be targeted by the synthesis modules.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Repair systems often focus on a small pre-defined class of bugs in order to reduce the search space.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Industrial use is limited owing to the computational cost of existing techniques.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The growth in complexity of designs increases the importance of formal verification techniques in the hardware industry.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] At present, formal verification is used by most or all leading hardware companies, but its use in the software industry is still languishing.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] This could be attributed to the greater need in the hardware industry, where errors have greater commercial significance.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Because of the potential subtle interactions between components, it is increasingly difficult to exercise a realistic set of possibilities by simulation.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Important aspects of hardware design are amenable to automated proof methods, making formal verification easier to introduce and more productive.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] As of 2011, several operating systems have been formally verified: NICTA's Secure Embedded L4 microkernel, sold commercially as seL4 by OK Labs; OSEK/VDX based real-time operating system ORIENTAIS by East China Normal University; Green Hills Software's Integrity operating system; and SYSGO's PikeOS.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] In 2016, a team led by Zhong Shao at Yale developed a formally verified operating system kernel called CertiKOS.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] As of 2017, formal verification has been applied to the design of large computer networks through a mathematical model of the network, and as part of a new network technology category, intent-based networking.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] Network software vendors that offer formal verification solutions include Cisco Forward Networks and Veriflow Systems.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The SPARK programming language provides a toolset which enables software development with formal verification and is used in several high-integrity systems.
[src:lean-prover/formal-verification] The CompCert C compiler is a formally verified C compiler implementing the majority of ISO C.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In computer science and mathematical logic, a **proof assistant** or **interactive theorem prover** is a software tool to assist with the development of formal proofs by human–machine collaboration.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] This involves some sort of interactive proof editor, or other interface, with which a human can guide the search for proofs, the details of which are stored in, and some steps provided by, a computer.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] A recent effort within this field is making these tools use artificial intelligence to automate the formalization of ordinary mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Because of this small size, some automated proof checking systems can have less than a thousand lines of core code, and are thus themselves amenable to both hand-checking and automated software verification.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The Mizar system, HOL Light, and Metamath are examples of automated proof checking systems.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automated proof checking can be done either as a batch operation, or interactively, as part of an interactive theorem proving system.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automath, which was developed by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn starting in 1967, is often considered the first proof checker and the first system to utilize the Curry–Howard correspondence between programs and proofs.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Automath was used by L.S. van Benthem Jutting in 1977 to formalize Landau's *Foundations of Analysis*, which was the first formalization of the real numbers.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In 1973, Robert Boyer and J Moore published *Proving Theorems about LISP Functions* which aimed to verify programs, not mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Their theorem prover is now known as ACL2.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] In the 1970s, Edinburgh LCF introduced the idea of using a functional programming language as the metalanguage for a theorem prover, and led to the HOL family of proof assistants.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The 1990s saw the rise of Rocq, (then known as Coq), which has been used for many large-scale formalization projects.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Since the late 2010s, Lean, a proof assistant strongly influenced by Rocq, has become another popular choice, especially for formalizing mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] A commonly used front-end for proof assistants was the Emacs-based Proof General, developed at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Nowadays, many provers include their own editor.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Rocq includes RocqIDE, which is based on OCaml/Gtk.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Isabelle includes Isabelle/jEdit, which is based on jEdit and the Isabelle/Scala infrastructure for document-oriented proof processing.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] More recently, Visual Studio Code extensions have been developed for Rocq, Isabelle by Makarius Wenzel, and for Lean 4 by the leanprover developers.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] Freek Wiedijk has been keeping a ranking of proof assistants by the amount of formalized theorems out of a list of 100 well-known theorems.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] As of September 2025, only six systems have formalized proofs of more than 70% of the theorems, namely Isabelle, HOL Light, Lean, Rocq, Metamath and Mizar.
[src:lean-prover/interactive-theorem-proving] The following is a list of notable proofs that have been formalized within proof assistants.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Lean's minimal trusted kernel guarantees absolute correctness in mathematical proof, software and hardware verification.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] From elementary concepts to cutting-edge research, Lean's expressive language and extensive built-in tools let users focus on the big picture rather than routine details.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Lean's metaprogramming capabilities enable users to extend the language with domain-specific notations and new proof automation techniques.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Lean lets you write precise, verifiable code and formal proofs.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Whether you are new or experienced, now is a great time to start.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] ArkLib, a project supported by the Ethereum Foundation, anchors a growing ecosystem of Lean libraries for formally verifying succinct non-interactive arguments of knowledge (SNARKs).
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] It mechanizes the subtle, probabilistic security proofs these cryptographic systems depend on, giving zk engineers and cryptography researchers machine-checked specifications and executable references.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] This brings high assurance to proof systems where a single soundness bug can be catastrophic.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Veil is an open-source multi-modal verification framework for distributed protocols, embedded in Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] In contrast to standalone verifiers, Veil uses Lean as a platform, combining symbolic and concrete model checking, SMT-based automated proofs, and interactive theorem proving in a single cohesive tool with foundational guarantees and rich in-editor feedback.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] It shows Lean is not just a proof assistant, but a platform for industrial-strength verifiers with great user experience.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] AWS uses Lean and verification-guided development to formally verify Cedar, the AWS authorization policy language.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] The approach involves creating executable models in Lean, proving security properties, and validating them against production code through differential testing.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] This achieves high assurance with minimal runtime overhead, demonstrating Lean's viability for verifying critical software.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Aeneas takes a novel approach to Rust verification.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Unlike other verification approaches that must reason about memory directly, Aeneas leverages Rust's rich type system to eliminate memory reasoning entirely for many Rust programs.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Mathlib is Lean's comprehensive mathematical library containing over a million lines of formalized mathematics spanning algebra, analysis, topology, probability, and computer science.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] This community-driven resource enables mathematicians to tackle frontier research problems and engineers to build verified systems by providing a rigorously verified foundation of mathematical knowledge that eliminates duplication of effort.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] The Fermat's Last Theorem project is formalizing one of mathematics' most complex proofs in Lean, demonstrating the proof assistant's capacity to handle frontier research mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] This ambitious work is creating formalized definitions for advanced number-theoretic objects, enabling mathematicians to build machine-verified proofs of cutting-edge results while establishing Lean as a powerful platform for mathematical collaboration.
[src:lean-prover/lean-lang-org] Lean FRO gratefully acknowledges support from **Alex Gerko**, Founder and CEO of XTX Markets, as well as from the following organizations.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean was developed primarily by Brazilian computer scientist Leonardo de Moura while employed by Microsoft Research and now Amazon Web Services and has had significant contributions from other coauthors and collaborators during its history.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Launched in 2013, initial versions of the language, later known as Lean 1 and 2, were experimental and contained features such as support for homotopy type theory-based foundations that were later dropped.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean 3 (first released Jan 20, 2017) was the first moderately stable version of Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] It was implemented primarily in C++ with some features written in Lean itself.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] After version 3.4.2, Lean 3 was officially end-of-lifed while development of Lean 4 began.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In this interim period members of the Lean community developed and released unofficial versions up to 3.51.1.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2021, Lean 4 was released, which was a reimplementation of the Lean theorem prover capable of producing C code which is then compiled, enabling the development of efficient domain-specific automation.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean 4 also contains a hygienic macro system and improved type class synthesis and memory management procedures over the previous version.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Another benefit compared to Lean 3 is the ability to avoid touching C++ code in order to modify the frontend and other key parts of the core system, as they are now all implemented in Lean and available to the end user to be overridden as needed.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean 4 is not backwards-compatible with Lean 3.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2023, the Lean FRO was formed, with the goals of improving the language's scalability and usability, and implementing proof automation.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2025, ACM SIGPLAN Programming Languages Software Award was awarded to Gabriel Ebner, Soonho Kong, Leo de Moura and Sebastian Ullrich for Lean, cited for its "significant impact on mathematics, hardware and software verification, and AI".
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2026, the *mathlib* library was awarded the Demailly prize for open science.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean includes many features useful for functional programming and theorem proving, such as dependent types, type classes, multi-threading, an expressive tactic language, and a module system.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] The official Lean standard library is called *Std* and contains common data structures and functions useful for programming, such as tree maps, hash maps, datetime functions, and concurrency primitives.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] The standard library is complemented by the community-maintained *batteries*, which implements additional data structures that may be used for both mathematical research and more conventional software development.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2017, a community-maintained project to develop a Lean library *mathlib* began, with the goal to digitize as much of pure mathematics as possible in one large cohesive library, up to research level mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] As of May 2025, mathlib had formalized over 210,000 theorems and 100,000 definitions in Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Other libraries include *CSLib* which is a theoretical computer science library, *SciLean* which is a library for scientific computing in Lean, and *PhysLib*, whose goal is to digitize physics using Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean integrates with Visual Studio Code, Neovim and Emacs.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Interfacing is done via a client-extension and Language Server Protocol server.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In these editors, Unicode symbols can be typed using LaTeX-like sequences, such as `\times` for "×".
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] The natural numbers can be defined as an inductive type.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] This definition is based on the Peano axioms and states that every natural number is either zero or the successor of some other natural number.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Addition of natural numbers can be defined recursively, using pattern matching.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Lean has received attention from mathematicians such as Thomas Hales, Kevin Buzzard, Terence Tao, and Heather Macbeth.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Hales is using it for his project, Formal Abstracts.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] One of the Xena Project's goals is to rewrite every theorem and proof in the undergraduate math curriculum of Imperial College London in Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Tao released a Lean companion to his real analysis textbook *Analysis I*, consisting of a formalization of selected sections of the mathematical text.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Macbeth is using Lean to teach students the fundamentals of mathematical proof with instant feedback.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2021, a team of researchers used Lean to verify the correctness of a proof by Peter Scholze in the area of condensed mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] The project garnered attention for formalizing a result at the cutting edge of mathematical research.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2023, Terence Tao used Lean to formalize a proof of the Polynomial Freiman-Ruzsa (PFR) conjecture, a result published by Tao and collaborators in the same year.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2026, Erdős Problems 728, 347, and 369 were solved using AI assistance and formally verified with Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Physlib aspires to be the definitive library for physics in Lean, akin to Mathlib for mathematics.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] It aims to be a comprehensive repository containing fundamental definitions, theorems, and calculations from physics.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Kevin Buzzard at Imperial College London says that formalisation is having a big impact on mathematics, and that there is no reason that theoretical physics can’t be treated in the same way.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2025, Joseph Tooby-Smith used Lean to discover an error in a paper published in 2006 on the stability of the Two-Higgs-doublet model (2HDM) potential.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2022, OpenAI and Meta AI independently created AI models to generate proofs of various high-school-level olympiad problems in Lean.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] Meta AI's model is available for public use with the Lean environment.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2023, Vlad Tenev and Tudor Achim co-founded startup Harmonic, which aims to reduce AI hallucinations by generating and checking Lean code.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In 2024, Google DeepMind created AlphaProof which proves mathematical statements in Lean at the level of a silver medalist at the International Mathematical Olympiad.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] This was the first AI system that achieved a medal-worthy performance on a math olympiad's problems.
[src:lean-prover/lean-proof-assistant] In April 2025, DeepSeek introduced DeepSeek-Prover-V2, an AI model designed for theorem proving in Lean 4, built on top of DeepSeek-V3.
[src:lean-prover/theorem-proving-in-lean4] This version of the text assumes you’re using Lean 4 (specifically `4.26.0`).
[src:lean-prover/theorem-proving-in-lean4] See the Quickstart section of the Lean documentation to install Lean.
[src:lean-prover/theorem-proving-in-lean4] The first version of this book was written for Lean 2, and the Lean 3 version is available here.
